Project Problem Statement - FMST¶

Problem Statement: Concrete Strength Prediction¶

Objective¶

To predict the concrete strength using the data available in file "concrete.csv". Apply feature engineering and model tuning to obtain a score above 85%.

Resources Available¶

The data for this project is available in file https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/concrete/compressive/. The same has been shared along with the course content.

Steps and Tasks:¶

Exploratory Data Quality Report Reflecting the Following:

  • Univariate analysis –data types and description of the independent attributes which should include (name, range of values observed, central values (mean and median), standard deviation and quartiles, analysis of the body of distributions/tails, missing values, outliers, duplicates(10 Marks)
  • Bi-variate analysis between the predictor variables and between the predictor variables and target column. Comment on your findings in terms of their relationship and degree of relation if any. Visualize the analysis using boxplots and pair plots, histograms, or density curves. (10 marks)
  • Feature Engineering techniques(10 marks)
    1. Identify opportunities (if any) to extract new features from existing features, drop a feature(if required) Hint: Feature Extraction, for example, consider a dataset with two features length and breadth. From this, we can extract a new feature Area which would be length * breadth.
    2. Get the data model ready and do a train test split.
    3. Decide on the complexity of the model, should it be a simple linear model in terms of parameters or would a quadratic or higher degree.

Creating the Model and Tuning It:¶

  • Algorithms that you think will be suitable for this project. Use Kfold Cross-Validation to evaluate model performance. Use appropriate metrics and make a DataFrame to compare models w.r.t their metrics. (at least 3 algorithms, one bagging and one boosting based algorithms have to be there). (15 marks)
  • Techniques employed to squeeze that extra performance out of the model without making it overfit. Use Grid Search or Random Search on any of the two models used above. Make a DataFrame to compare models after hyperparameter tuning and their metrics as above. (15 marks)

Features

  1. Cement (cement): kg in a m3 mixture.
  2. Blast Furnace Slag (slag): kg in a m3 mixture.
  3. Fly Ash (ash): kg in a m3 mixture.
  4. Water(water): kg in a m3 mixture.
  5. Superplasticizer (superplastic): kg in a m3 mixture.
  6. Coarse Aggregate (coarseagg): kg in a m3 mixture.
  7. Fine Aggregate (fineagg): kg in a m3 mixture.
  8. Age(age): Measured in days (1~365).
  9. Concrete compressive strength(strength): MPa (target variable)

Let us also create training and testing sets of scaled polynomial features to see if there is any impact when modeling

In [21]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures, StandardScaler

# create X and y for poly features
X_prep = df.iloc[:, 1:]
yp = df.cement

# scale X
ss = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = ss.fit_transform(X_prep)
X_scaled = pd.DataFrame(X_scaled, columns=X_prep.columns)

# create poly features to the 2nd degree
pf = PolynomialFeatures(2)
X_poly = pd.DataFrame(pf.fit_transform(X_scaled), columns=pf.get_feature_names(X_scaled.columns))
X_poly.drop('1', axis=1, inplace=True)

# splitting the polynomial features into training and testing data sets
Xp_train, Xp_test, yp_train, yp_test = train_test_split(X_poly, yp, test_size=0.25, random_state=14)

Create the model¶

Random forest¶

run random forest on the first train and test datasets (non-polynomial)

In [29]:
y_train = y_train.astype(int)
y_test = y_test.astype(int)
In [30]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
rf = RandomForestRegressor(criterion='mse', random_state=14)
In [31]:
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
rf_pred = rf.predict(X_test)
In [32]:
rf_train_r2 = rf.score(X_train, y_train)
rf_test_r2 = rf.score(X_test, y_test)
rf_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, rf_pred)
rf_rmse = np.sqrt(rf_mse)


rf_scores = [rf_train_r2, rf_test_r2, rf_mse, rf_rmse]
rf_mets = ['Train r squared', 'Test r squared', 'MSE', 'RMSE']

rf_metrics_df = pd.DataFrame({'Metrics': rf_mets, 'Scores': rf_scores})
rf_metrics_df

  • the r squared scores are quite high for random forest. This is good. I would, however, like to improve the RMSE of this model. I will first run kfold cross validation on the random forest model, and then I will use Random Search to accomplish this

KFold Cross Validation¶

In [50]:
# Evaluate using Cross Validation
from sklearn import model_selection
import warnings

warnings.simplefilter('ignore')
In [51]:
seed = 14
kfold = model_selection.KFold(n_splits=20, random_state=seed)
In [52]:
results = model_selection.cross_val_score(rf, X, y, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', cv=kfold)
print("Mean Square Error: %.3f" % (np.sqrt(-results.mean())))

Mean Square Error: 19.466
  • even after running cross validation, the rmse hovers right around 19

Random Search¶

In [53]:
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
from scipy.stats import randint as sp_randint

make a parameter dictionary for the random forest algorithm

In [54]:
rf_params = {"max_depth": [5, None],
              "max_features": [sp_randint(1, 9), 'auto'],
              "min_samples_split": sp_randint(2, 10),
              "min_samples_leaf": sp_randint(1, 10),
              "bootstrap": [True, False],
              "n_estimators": [10, 100],
              "criterion": ['mse']}

run the random search based on these parameter ranges

In [55]:
samples = 10  
rand_search = RandomizedSearchCV(rf, param_distributions=rf_params, n_iter=samples, random_state=14)
